crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature fires on the presence of Base64 encoded URI prefixes (http:// and https://) across any file. The simple presence of such strings is not inherently an indicator of malicious content, but is worth further investigation.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (GNU/Linux), statically linked, BuildID[sha1]=135042d99cdd63eedf1c83976482c5fe6fa0c34e, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is an IRC bot with extensive backdoor capabilities. It connects to an IRC server, joins a hardcoded channel ('#masspwn'), and awaits commands. Key malicious behaviors include: arbitrary command execution via '/bin/sh', establishing a reverse shell ('nc %s -e /bin/sh'), downloading and executing files from URLs into '/var/bin', and self-updating by compiling received C source code in '/tmp'. The malware also achieves persistence by modifying '/etc/rc.d/rc.local' or '/etc/rc.conf' and masquerades its process name as 'kworker/08:15-events' to evade detection.
